{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Installation · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Installation</h1>
    <p class="lead">Stisla ships in two pieces. A universal stylesheet and a vanilla JS runtime. Drop them in via CDN, install from a package manager, or fork the Sass source.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>Pick a bundle</h2>
    <p>Stisla ships two bundles, the same pair of packages with two different entry files. Pick one before you start.</p>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Bundle</th>
            <th width="30%">Gzip CSS + JS</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Core.</strong> Every component except the optional ones (carousel, date-picker, command palette, etc.).</td>
            <td>~29 KB + ~27 KB</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Full.</strong> Core plus every optional component in one bundle. One install line that gives you everything.</td>
            <td>~30 KB + ~37 KB</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>If you&rsquo;re not sure, pick core. Adding an optional component later is just one extra import; you don&rsquo;t need to swap the bundle.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Using CDN</h2>
    <p>No build step. Drop the bundles into a plain HTML page.</p>

    <h3>Core</h3>
    <p>Two tags. One for the core stylesheet in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>, one for the runtime at the end of the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code>. That covers every component except the optional ones.</p>
    {% call ui.code(title='index.html') %}
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <title>Stisla starter</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/css@3/dist/stisla.css">
  </head>
  <body>
    <button type="button" class="btn btn--primary">Hello</button>

    <script type="module" src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/vanilla@3/dist/stisla.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Full</h3>
    <p>The same two tags, swapped to the <code>-full</code> filenames. You get every component, optionals included, with no extra setup.</p>
    {% call ui.code() %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/css@3/dist/stisla-full.css">
<script type="module" src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/vanilla@3/dist/stisla-full.js"></script>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Core plus individual optionals</h3>
    <p>Load the core bundle and tack on the optional components you actually use. Each optional ships its own CSS and JS file under <code>dist/components/</code>, next to the main bundle.</p>
    {% call ui.code() %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/css@3/dist/stisla.css">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/css@3/dist/components/carousel.css">

<script type="module" src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/vanilla@3/dist/stisla.js"></script>
<script type="module" src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@stisla/vanilla@3/dist/components/carousel.js"></script>
    {% endcall %}

    <p>The <code>@3</code> tag follows the latest 3.x release. Pin to <code>@3.0.0-beta.1</code> (or any future exact version) for reproducible builds.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Using package manager</h2>
    <p>The same two bundles, installed and bundled by your tool of choice. Stisla ships two scoped packages. <code>@stisla/css</code> holds the universal stylesheet, and <code>@stisla/vanilla</code> is the JS runtime that drives it.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='bash') %}
npm install @stisla/css @stisla/vanilla
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The two packages share a version. <code>@stisla/vanilla</code> declares <code>@stisla/css</code> as a peer dependency pinned to the matching version, so if the pair doesn&rsquo;t match you find out at install time instead of silently at runtime.</p>

    <h3>Core</h3>
    <p>Import the core CSS and the core runtime once at your app entry. That covers every component except the optional ones. Your bundler resolves both to the pre-compiled files inside each package.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='js', title='main.js') %}
import '@stisla/css';
import '@stisla/vanilla';
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Full</h3>
    <p>The same two imports, with <code>/full</code> on each subpath. You get every component, optionals included, with no extra setup.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='js') %}
import '@stisla/css/full';
import '@stisla/vanilla/full';
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Core plus individual optionals</h3>
    <p>Start from core and add one extra import per optional component you actually use. The bundle stays small for everything you skip, and tree-shaking handles the rest.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='js') %}
import '@stisla/css';
import '@stisla/vanilla';

import '@stisla/css/components/carousel';
import '@stisla/vanilla/components/carousel';
    {% endcall %}

    <p>Once you have the bundle loaded, head to the <a class="link" href="/javascript">JavaScript</a> page for how to drive components from markup or from JS.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Sass source</h2>
    <p>You don&rsquo;t need Sass for most customization. Picking a primary color, changing the radius, or swapping density is a single CSS variable override on <code>:root</code> and takes effect at runtime. The pre-compiled bundle above is the right entry for that.</p>
    <p>Reach for the Sass source when you need one of:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Changing breakpoint sizes (media queries can&rsquo;t read CSS variables, so breakpoints live in Sass).</li>
      <li>Forking a bundle entry to drop components you don&rsquo;t use, shaving the CSS payload further than tree-shaking can.</li>
      <li>Rewriting a component from the ground up while keeping the rest of the system intact.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The Sass source ships inside <code>@stisla/css</code> alongside the compiled CSS. Import a bundle entry from your own stylesheet instead of the <code>.css</code> file.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss', title='your-app.scss') %}
@use '@stisla/css/scss/bundles/stisla';
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The <a class="link" href="/optimization">Optimization</a> page walks through the fork-and-drop recipe with real before/after byte counts.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Browser support</h2>
    <p>Safari 16.4 or newer, Chrome 111 or newer, and Firefox 121 or newer. No polyfills. The features Stisla relies on (OKLCH, <code>color-mix</code>, <code>:has()</code>, <code>@layer</code>, container queries, <code>inert</code>) are stable across that range. If you need to support older browsers, falling back to an earlier version of the framework won&rsquo;t help, because the runtime token surface is what makes Stisla what it is.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What&rsquo;s next</h2>
    <p>Learn how <a class="link" href="/javascript">JavaScript</a> wires up components, pick a <a class="link" href="/customization">primary color</a>, or jump straight into the <a class="link" href="/button">component pages</a>.</p>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
